Import and QC of SimKumar

Load and process data set SimKumar (Kumar 2014)

suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(MultiAssayExperiment)
  library(scater)
  library(dplyr)
  library(tidyr)
  library(plyr)
  library(scran)
  library(cowplot)
  library(tibble)
  library(splatter)
})

Load MultiAssayExperiment object

(maex <- readRDS("../../data/data_raw/GSE60749-GPL13112.rds"))
## A MultiAssayExperiment object of 2 listed
##  experiments with user-defined names and respective classes. 
##  Containing an ExperimentList class object of length 2: 
##  [1] gene: RangedSummarizedExperiment with 45686 rows and 268 columns 
##  [2] tx: RangedSummarizedExperiment with 113560 rows and 268 columns 
## Features: 
##  experiments() - obtain the ExperimentList instance 
##  colData() - the primary/phenotype DataFrame 
##  sampleMap() - the sample availability DataFrame 
##  `$`, `[`, `[[` - extract colData columns, subset, or experiment 
##  *Format() - convert into a long or wide DataFrame 
##  assays() - convert ExperimentList to a SimpleList of matrices
## Extract the gene-level TPM and the counts obtaines by scaling the TPMs
cts <- assays(experiments(maex)[["gene"]])[["count_lstpm"]]

## Extract the phenotype data. Here, we are interested in the three culture conditions
phn <- colData(maex)
phn$phenoid <- as.character(interaction(as.data.frame(phn[, c("source_name_ch1",
                                                              "characteristics_ch1.1")])))
## Simplify labels
phn$phenoid <-  plyr::revalue(
  phn$phenoid , 
  c("Dgcr8 knockout mouse embryonic stem cells.culture conditions: serum+LIF" = "Dgcr8 knockout mouse serum+LIF", 
    "v6.5 mouse embryonic stem cells.culture conditions: 2i+LIF" = "v6.5 mouse 2i+LIF",
    "v6.5 mouse embryonic stem cells.culture conditions: serum+LIF" = "v6.5 mouse serum+LIF")
)
table(phn$phenoid)
## 
## Dgcr8 knockout mouse serum+LIF              v6.5 mouse 2i+LIF 
##                             84                             94 
##           v6.5 mouse serum+LIF 
##                             90

Extract one subpopulation

sub.cts <- cts[, phn$phenoid == "v6.5 mouse 2i+LIF"]
dim(sub.cts)
## [1] 45686    94

Remove the ERCC spike-ins

is.spike <- grepl("^ERCC", rownames(sub.cts))
sub.cts <- sub.cts[!is.spike, ]

Estimate parameters for simulation

(params <- splatEstimate(sub.cts))

Simulate new counts

sce <- splatSimulate(params = params, batchCells = 500,
                     group.prob = c(0.1, 0.15, 0.5, 0.25), 
                     method = "groups", de.prob = c(0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.4),
                     verbose = FALSE)
logcounts(sce) <- log2(calculateCPM(sce) + 1)
## Warning in calculateCPM(sce): no size factors for non-control genes, using
## library sizes instead
sce$phenoid <- colData(sce)$Group

Exclude features that are not expressed

keep_features <- rowSums(counts(sce) > 0) >= 1
table(keep_features)
## keep_features
## FALSE  TRUE 
##  1872 43722
sce <- sce[keep_features, ]
dim(sce)
## [1] 43722   500

Calculate QC metrics

sce <- calculateQCMetrics(sce)

Quality control on cells

size.med <- median(log10(sce$total_counts), na.rm = TRUE)
size.mad <- mad(log10(sce$total_counts), center = size.med, na.rm = TRUE)
lower.limit.size <- 10^(size.med - 3 * size.mad)/1e6
    
feature.med <- median(log10(sce$total_features), na.rm = TRUE)
feature.mad <- mad(log10(sce$total_features), center = size.med, na.rm = TRUE)
lower.limit.feat <- 10^(feature.med - 3 * feature.mad)

ggplot(as.data.frame(colData(sce)), aes(x = total_counts/1e6)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, fill = "grey80") + xlab("Library size (million reads)") + 
  ylab("Number of cells") + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = lower.limit.size, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") + 
  theme_bw()

ggplot(as.data.frame(colData(sce)), aes(x = total_features)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, fill = "grey80") + xlab("Number of detected features") + 
  ylab("Number of cells") + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = lower.limit.feat, color = "red", linetype = "dashed") + 
  theme_bw()

Quality control using PCA and highest expressed genes

We create a PCA plot based the quality metrics for each cell, e.g., the total number of reads, the total number of features and the proportion of mitochondrial or spike-in reads.

p1 <- scater::plotPCA(sce, exprs_values = "logcounts",
                      selected_variables = "pdata",colour_by = "phenoid") + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") + 
  guides(color = guide_legend(nrow = 3, byrow = TRUE))
## Warning in .disambiguate_args(...): non-plotting arguments like
## 'selected_variables' should go in 'run_args'
p2 <- scater::plotQC(sce, type = "find-pcs", variable = "total_features")

Filter dataset

We remove cells with log-library sizes that are more than 3 median absolute deviations (MADs) below the median log-library size.

libsize.drop <- isOutlier(sce$total_counts, nmads = 3, type = "lower", log = TRUE)
feature.drop <- isOutlier(sce$total_features, nmads = 3, type = "lower", log = TRUE)
table(libsize.drop, feature.drop)
##             feature.drop
## libsize.drop FALSE TRUE
##        FALSE   498    0
##        TRUE      0    2

We also filter out cells with a large fraction of ERCC reads.

sce <- sce[, !(libsize.drop | feature.drop)]

data.frame(ByLibSize = sum(libsize.drop), ByFeature = sum(feature.drop),
           Remaining = ncol(sce))
##   ByLibSize ByFeature Remaining
## 1         2         2       498

Quality control using PCA and highest expressed genes

Using the filtered data, we make a PCA plot based the quality metrics for each cell, e.g., the total number of reads, the total number of features and the proportion of mitochondrial or spike-in reads.

p3 <- plotQC(sce, type = "highest-expression", n = 50)
plotQC(sce, type = "exprs-freq-vs-mean")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam'

Gene filtering

ave.counts <- rowMeans(counts(sce))
keep <- ave.counts >= 1
sum(keep)
## [1] 31219
df <- data.frame(ave.counts = log10(ave.counts))

p4 <- ggplot(df, aes(x = ave.counts)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5) + 
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = log10(1), color = "red")) +
  guides(color = "none") + labs(x = expression(Log[10]~"average count"), 
                                y = "Number of genes")

sce.red <- sce[keep, ]

Data normalization

sce <- computeSumFactors(sce, sizes = c(20, 40, 60, 80))
summary(sizeFactors(sce))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.7037  0.8947  0.9870  1.0000  1.0945  1.4977
sce.red <- computeSumFactors(sce.red, sizes = c(20, 40, 60, 80))
summary(sizeFactors(sce.red))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.7128  0.8969  0.9837  1.0000  1.0939  1.5092
ggplot(data.frame(tc = sce$total_counts/1e6, 
                  sf = sizeFactors(sce)), aes(x = sf, y = tc)) + 
  geom_point() + xlab("Size factor") + ylab("Library size (million reads)") + 
  scale_x_log10() + scale_y_log10()

ggplot(data.frame(tc = sce.red$total_counts/1e6, 
                  sf = sizeFactors(sce.red)), aes(x = sf, y = tc)) + 
  geom_point() + xlab("Size factor") + ylab("Library size (million reads)") + 
  scale_x_log10() + scale_y_log10()

sce <- normalise(sce)
sce.red <- normalise(sce.red)

Plot the proportion of explained variances

expl_vars <- c("phenoid", "log10_total_counts", "log10_total_features", "pct_dropout",
               "pct_counts_top_200_features", "log10_counts_feature_controls",
               "pct_counts_feature_controls")
p5 <- plotQC(sce.red, type = "explanatory-variables", variables = expl_vars)

plot.qc <- plot_grid(p1, p2, p3, p4, p5, p6, ncol = 2, labels = "auto")
